   Vicentini Viana},
Title = {Multispectral Images for Differentiation of Lettuce Plants Inoculated
   With Phosphate-Solubilizing Fungi Under Different Phosphorus Doses},
Journal = {IEEE ACCESS},
Year = {2026},
Volume = {14},
Pages = {29836-29852},
Abstract = {Advanced technologies, such as remote sensing, have become prominent
   tools for monitoring various agricultural crops. However, few studies
   have investigated the potential of low-cost multispectral sensors for
   discriminating treatments involving bioinput applications, particularly
   in lettuce (Lactuca sativa) cultivation. This study aimed to evaluate
   the potential of multispectral images acquired by low-cost sensors,
   combined with machine learning techniques, for discriminating treatments
   applied to lettuce plants, considering different inoculation methods of
   the fungus Aspergillus niger and variations in phosphorus fertilization
   doses. The experiment was conducted in 2021 under a 6 \& times;3
   factorial design, including six inoculation methods of A. niger (no
   inoculation; seed treatment with conidial suspension; granular
   inoculation with 4 \& times;10(2) and 4 \& times;106 conidia g(-1) at
   transplanting; and inoculation with conidial suspensions at 4 \&
   times;102 and 4 \& times;106 conidia mL(-1) at transplanting) and three
   phosphorus doses (0, 50, and 100\%). During plant development, images
   were captured with an RGB camera and a MAPIR Survey 3W multispectral
   camera on days 5, 12, 19, 26, and 33 after transplanting. For treatment
   discrimination, average reflectance values of spectral bands were
   extracted, and vegetation indices were computed. Classification was
   performed using machine learning algorithms in the Weka software,
   considering three distinct scenarios. The Random Forest model showed the
   best performance, particularly when combining RGB and RGN sensor
   attributes, achieving overall accuracies of 65.35\%, 79.57\%, and
   94.24\% in the respective scenarios. This study reinforces the potential
   of spectral imaging for crop monitoring and management.},
